The word '''''caravan''''' has a [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] root and in ancient times it was used for a group of people who were traveling by camel or horse on the [[silk road]].  The word is derived from Karwan: ''Kar ''means ''mission'' or ''pursuit'' and ''wan'' means ''those people'' and ''guardian''. A '''caravanserai''' or '''karwansiray''' (also [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]]), means a ''home'' or ''shelter'' for caravans. Caravans are often formed by militaries as well. A caravansara was a roadside [[inn]] where caravans could rest and recover from the day's journey. Some nomadic peoples known for caravan living include the [[Roma people]], the [[Irish traveller]]s, nomadic [[Kurds]], the [[Bedouin]]s, the [[Yeniche (people)|Yeniche people]], and the [[Quinqui]].